-- Emerging-Market Stocks Rise on Asian Company Profits, U.S. Jobless Claims
-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n   a n d   J a s o n   W e b b
-- 2010-10-28T21:49:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/emerging-market-stocks-rise-on-asian-company-profits-u-s-jobless-claims.html
Emerging-market stocks rose, lifting
the benchmark index from its biggest drop since August, after
Asian companies reported earnings increases and applications for
U.S. unemployment benefits unexpectedly fell last week.  The  MSCI Emerging Markets Index  gained 0.4 percent to
1,102.82 at 5 p.m. New York time, rebounding from yesterday’s
1.6 percent retreat. Taiwan’s  Taiex Index  jumped 0.8 percent to
the highest since Jan. 15. The  MSCI China Index , tracking mainly
Hong Kong-traded shares of Chinese companies, added 0.2 percent.
Brazil’s  Bovespa  stock index declined 0.4 percent, erasing an
earlier advance and retreating for a second day.  Bank of China Ltd.  rallied in Hong Kong as third-quarter
profit beat analysts’ estimates.  Unimicron Technology Corp. , a
Taiwanese maker of printed circuit boards, jumped after posting
a 57 percent profit gain. The Hungarian Forint appreciated 1.8
percent and the South African rand gained 0.9 percent against
the dollar as the U.S. central bank was due to consider further
purchases of Treasury bonds at its Federal Open Market Committee
meeting from Nov. 2 to Nov. 3.  “Emerging markets have outperformed on expectations of
faster economic and earnings growth,” said  Paul Joseph Garcia ,
who helps manage $1.86 billion as chief investment officer at
ING Investment Management Ltd.’s Manila unit.  Initial jobless  claims  decreased by 21,000 to 434,000 in
the week ended Oct. 23, the lowest since early July, U.S. Labor
Department figures showed today. Economists had forecast claims
would increase to 455,000 from a previously reported 452,000 for
the prior week, according to the  median  of 47 projections in a
Bloomberg News survey.  The MSCI emerging nations’ gauge has climbed 11 percent
this year, almost three times the 4.3 percent gain in the MSCI
World Index of shares in developed markets. Investors are
banking on developing economies’ higher growth rates to yield
better returns amid near-zero U.S. borrowing costs.  Bank of China  Bank of China advanced 2.2 percent after profit surged 29
percent to a record 27.2 billion yuan ($4.07 billion), beating
the 23.9 billion yuan median estimate of nine analysts surveyed
by Bloomberg News.  Redecard SA, Brazil’s second-largest card-payment processor
by market value, tumbled 5.7 percent, the most since May. Cielo
SA, Redecard’s larger competitor, dropped 1.7 percent. Vale, the
world’s biggest iron ore producer, lost 1.7 percent.  Taiwan’s Unimicron Technology jumped 6.9 percent after
third-quarter profit surged to NT$2.10 billion ($69 million).  Bulgarian  stocks  rallied the most in 14 months after the
government changed plans to transfer some private pension funds
to state control. The  Sofix  Index climbed 3.9 percent, bringing
its gain to 4.9 percent in the three days since Oct. 25, when
the gauge closed at its lowest since April 2009.  Kaolin AD , a
mining company, surged 16 percent.  The  ISE National 100  Index added 0.3 percent in Istanbul
after falling as much as 1.9 percent earlier before a 1 1/2-day
holiday starting after the morning session.  To contact the reporters on this story:
